<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-032-280 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 432 447</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Oct 17 1991 pA23(W) pA23(E) 24 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Innovation, a casualty at IBM. (XyQuest Inc. tries to release theSignature word processing software package under an agreement withIBM) (Counterpoint)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Judis, John B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>IBM and XyQuest Inc sign an agreement to jointly develop a wordprocessing software package, but the product has been postponedindefinitely.andP;  The delay exemplifies how large corporations stiflethe creativity of innovative start-ups.andP;  XyQuest founder DavidErickson developed the XyWrite word processing product in Jun 1982and decided, together with John Hild, to market it.andP;  Erickson wasworking on XyWrite IV in 1989, but realized that without propermarketing, the product would never become a mainstream success.andO;While XyWrite offered sophisticated features such as automaticfootnoting and two on-screen windows, it was difficult to learnand many did not even know it existed.andP;  IBM was in need of a wordprocessor to market since its own Display Write 5 was not a strongrival to such products as Microsoft Corp's Word and WordPerfect.andO;The agreement between IBM and XyQuest called for the developmentof a new program called Signature, to be modeled on XyWrite IV.andO;Signature has undergone a series of delays, and IBM may abandon itentirely.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Contracts)XYQUEST Inc. (Contracts).andO;Product:   XyWrite IV (Word processing software) (Product development)Signature (Word processing software) (Product development).andO;Topic:     Cooperative AgreementProduct DevelopmentProduct DelayOrganization StructurePartnershipWord processing software.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>